## Priority Guidelines

### Decision Tree

```
Is this a test case?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Priority 90-100
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Continue

Does it have 2+ Call-IDs?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Priority 75-80
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Continue

Does it have RTP Engine (XCC header)?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Priority 65-75
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Continue

Is it direct media (no RTP Engine)?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Priority 60-65
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Continue

Is it a fallback/recovery case?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Priority 30-50
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Continue

Is it a generic catch-all?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Priority 10-20
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Priority 0 (unknown)
```

### Priority Ranges Summary

| Priority | Category | Examples |
|----------|----------|----------|
| 100 | Tests | `test_templates_*` |
| 90-95 | Reserved | Future use |
| 80-89 | High-specificity | Multi Call-ID, blocked XCC |
| 70-79 | RTP Engine + XCC | `inbound_xcc`, `early_media_183` |
| 60-69 | Direct media | `inbound_no_xcc`, `reinvite_detection` |
| 50-59 | PSTN carriers | `inbound_pstn_carrier` |
| 40-49 | RTP Engine fallbacks | `inbound_with_rtp_engine-fallback` |
| 30-39 | General fallbacks | `response_hop_fallback` |
| 10-29 | Generic direction | `generic_inbound` |
| 0-9 | Unknown | `unknown` (priority 0) |

### Ordering Rules

1. **Highest priority first**: Cases evaluated from priority 100 ‚Üí 0
2. **First match wins**: Evaluation stops at first matching case
3. **Alphabetical tie-breaker**: Same priority = alphabetical order by filename
4. **Disabled cases skipped**: `enabled: false` cases never evaluated

### Priority Anti-Patterns

‚ùå **Don't**:
- Set all cases to priority 50 (no ordering)
- Use priorities > 100 (reserved for system)
- Set fallback cases higher than specific cases
- Forget to test priority changes

‚úÖ **Do**:
- Use priority ranges as documented
- Test case order with `make start` (check logs)
- Keep test cases at priority 90+ so they're easy to identify
- Document why you set a specific priority

